{"title_page": "Kathleen Pelham Burn", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{use dmy|date=March 2020}}\n{{British barrelled name|Pelham Burn}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = Lady\n| name               = Kathleen Pelham Burn\n| honorific_suffix   = Countess of Drogheda, [[CBE]] [[Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]]\n| image              = Kathleen Pelham Burn 1918.jpg\n| other_names        = Lady Kathleen Moore\n| birth_date         = 1887\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|df=y|1966|03|18|1887}}\n| spouse             = [[Henry Moore, 10th Earl of Drogheda]] (1909\u20131922)<br />Guillermo de Landa y Escandon (1922\u20131929)\n| children           = [[Charles Moore, 11th Earl of Drogheda]]<br />Lady Patricia Doreen Moore\n}}\n'''Kathleen Pelham Burn Moore, Countess of Drogheda''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|CMG}} (1887&nbsp;\u2013 18 March 1966) was a British socialite, aviator, and sportswoman. She was one of the \"[[bright young things]]\".\n\n== Biography ==\nPelham Burn was interested in various pursuits. [[Turtle Bunbury]] describes her as \"an enigmatic cigarette-smoking 20th century lady famous for dabbling in the occult\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.turtlebunbury.com/history/history_family/hist_family_mooredrogheda.html|title=Turtle Bunbury \u2013 Award-winning travel writer, historian and author based in Ireland|website=turtlebunbury.com|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBorn to a wealthy family (her mother's side of mining, her father's Scottish landowners), she had the ability to \"pursue her manifold interests with great vigour\" from her youth.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Cork|first=Richard Graham|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=orwBWXvJ0eUC&pg=PA178&lpg=PA178&dq=Kathleen+Pelham+Burn&source=bl&ots=jorf_3T7CZ&sig=ACfU3U2sPobNxGwl3rybkJweV7Pfm-63lQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi1x77Jnf_nAhU6QhUIHT8TC-04FBDoATACegQICxAB#v=onepage&q=drogheda&f=false|title=Art Beyond the Gallery in Early 20th Century England|publisher=Yale University Press|year=1985|isbn=978-0-300-03236-9}}</ref> She was particularly interested in flying;<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> she became one of the first women to fly as a passenger in a plane.<ref name=\":1\" /> She later became known as \"the Flying Countess\" for her many passenger journeys and then for flying in aircraft exhibitions across the UK and Ireland to raise money for the [[Royal Air Force]] during [[World War II]].<ref name=\"Tatler\">{{cite magazine|work=[[Tatler]]|title=A Flying Countess Who has Done Excellent Work on Behalf of R.A.F.|author=<!--Not given-->|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001852/19181218/014/0011|access-date=12 April 2020|url-access=subscription|page=11|date=18 December 1918}}</ref> She had also worked for aviation charities during [[World War I]], and was a guest at [[Edward Maitland (RAF officer)|Edward Maitland]]'s pre-flight celebrations of the [[R33-class airship#R34|R34]] successfully attempting the [[Transatlantic flight#First transatlantic flights|first return Atlantic crossing]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rosie|first=George|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gLO8BQAAQBAJ&pg=PT68&lpg=PT68&dq=Kathleen+Pelham+Burn&source=bl&ots=YzBWRUU8nu&sig=ACfU3U3eOJLB2zHs0qA3I8HY4Fik0fOK5A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi1x77Jnf_nAhU6QhUIHT8TC-04FBDoATABegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=Kathleen%20Pelham%20Burn&f=false|title=The Flight of the Titan: The Story of the R34|date=10 December 2012|publisher=Birlinn|isbn=978-0-85790-561-1}}</ref>\n\nHer other interests included driving fashionable cars around London and playing tennis at [[All England Lawn Tennis and Croquet Club]] (Wimbledon), being one of its first members.<ref name=\":1\" /> She competed in [[The Championships, Wimbledon]] once, in [[1914 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1914]], though she went out in the second round.<ref name=\"Wimbledon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/static/pdfs/archive/draws/1914_LS_A4.pdf|title=The Championships 1914: Ladies' All-Comers' Singles|website=[[The Championships, Wimbledon]]|access-date=12 April 2020|author=<!--No author-->}}</ref> She also played a lot of golf,<ref name=\":1\" /> and was a lover of contemporary art, but not music or literature.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBunbury notes that she held [[s\u00e9ance]]s that were social events, attended by celebrities of the day, including [[Jacob Epstein]], [[Augustus John]], and [[Wyndham Lewis]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1919 she was appointed [[Order of St Michael and St George|Companion, Order of St. Michael and St. George]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p25436.htm#c254359.1|title=Kathleen Pelham Burn|date=n.d.|website=thepeerage.com|url-status=live|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref> She was also a [[Order of the British Empire|Commander of the Order of the British Empire]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/drogheda1661.htm|title=Drogheda, Earl of (I, 1661)|website=cracroftspeerage.co.uk|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Walford|first=Edward|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TuHIDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA399&lpg=PA399&dq=Kathleen+Pelham-Burn+CBE&source=bl&ots=ca5k4B4KSs&sig=ACfU3U3HCBWxfiMh5dPZrhsCFDGfAAJ_3g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwju3-2Ysf_nAhUdQRUIHRugDY8Q6AEwA3oECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=Kathleen%20Pelham-Burn%20CBE&f=false|title=The county families of the United Kingdom; or, Royal manual of the titled and untitled aristocracy of England, Wales, Scotland, and Ireland|publisher=Dalcassian Publishing Company|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Kathleen Pelham Burns, cameo portrait LCCN2014683495 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|150px|Pelham Burn in 1909]]\nPelham Burn's first husband was the Anglo-Irish civil servant [[Henry Moore, 10th Earl of Drogheda|Henry Ponsonby Moore, 10th Earl of Drogheda]]. They wed on 3 March 1909 and divorced in 1922; Pelham Burn filed for divorce in 1921 on account of Henry's unfaithfulness. The marriage gave two children: [[Charles Moore, 11th Earl of Drogheda|Charles]] (born 1910) and Patricia (born 1912), whom Pelham Burn was granted custody of in the divorce.<ref name=\":3\" /> The couple had been married in \"a grand ceremony in [[St Giles' Cathedral|St. Giles's Cathedral]], Edinburgh\" and lived in London at 40 [[Wilton Crescent]];<ref name=\":1\" /> they also owned [[Moore Abbey]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.askaboutireland.ie/reading-room/history-heritage/big-houses-of-ireland/moore-abbey/20th-century/|title=20th Century|website=askaboutireland.ie|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref> Charles later said that his parents seemed to live separate lives and their divorce was not surprising.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn 31 August 1922, Pelham Burn married Guillermo \"Billy\" de Landa y Escandon, a Mexican playboy and son of former [[Mexico City]] Governor [[Guillermo Landa y Escand\u00f3n]]. They divorced in 1929.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nShe is accounted by her son as being [[bisexual]], as he wrote: \"All her life she was attracted by men and women [...] she knew intimately [[Donald Campbell]], [[Alan Cobham]], [[Kaye Don]], [[Jim Mollison]], [[Amy Johnson]], and plenty of others besides.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> She may have also had an affair with Wyndham Lewis during her first marriage,<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> whom she also commissioned for art against her husband's wishes.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|ie}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = Anne Tower Moir\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = [[Earl of Drogheda|Countess of Drogheda]]\n| years = 1909\u20131922\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = Olive Mary Paget\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pelham Burn, Kathleen, Drogheda, Countess of}}\n[[Category:1887 births]]\n[[Category:1966 deaths]]\n[[Category:Aviation pioneers]]\n[[Category:Bisexual women]]\n[[Category:British countesses]]\n[[Category:British female aviators]]\n[[Category:British female tennis players]]\n[[Category:British socialites]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Irish countesses]]\n[[Category:Scottish noblewomen]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{use dmy|date=March 2020}}\n{{British barrelled name|Pelham Burn}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = Lady\n| name               = Kathleen Pelham Burn Moore\n| honorific_suffix   = Countess of Drogheda, [[CBE]] [[Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]]\n| image              = Kathleen Pelham Burn 1918.jpg\n| other_names        = Lady Kathleen Moore\n| birth_date         = 1887\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|df=y|1966|03|18|1887}}\n| spouse             = [[Henry Moore, 10th Earl of Drogheda]] (1909\u20131922)<br />Guillermo de Landa y Escandon (1922\u20131929)\n| children           = [[Charles Moore, 11th Earl of Drogheda]]<br />Lady Patricia Doreen Moore\n}}\n'''Kathleen Pelham Burn Moore, Countess of Drogheda''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|CMG}} (1887&nbsp;\u2013 18 March 1966) was a British socialite, aviator, and sportswoman. She was one of the \"[[bright young things]]\".\n\n== Biography ==\nPelham Burn was interested in various pursuits. [[Turtle Bunbury]] describes her as \"an enigmatic cigarette-smoking 20th century lady famous for dabbling in the occult\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.turtlebunbury.com/history/history_family/hist_family_mooredrogheda.html|title=Turtle Bunbury \u2013 Award-winning travel writer, historian and author based in Ireland|website=turtlebunbury.com|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBorn to a wealthy family (her mother's side of mining, her father's Scottish landowners), she had the ability to \"pursue her manifold interests with great vigour\" from her youth.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Cork|first=Richard Graham|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=orwBWXvJ0eUC&pg=PA178&lpg=PA178&dq=Kathleen+Pelham+Burn&source=bl&ots=jorf_3T7CZ&sig=ACfU3U2sPobNxGwl3rybkJweV7Pfm-63lQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi1x77Jnf_nAhU6QhUIHT8TC-04FBDoATACegQICxAB#v=onepage&q=drogheda&f=false|title=Art Beyond the Gallery in Early 20th Century England|publisher=Yale University Press|year=1985|isbn=978-0-300-03236-9}}</ref> She was particularly interested in flying;<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> she became one of the first women to fly as a passenger in a plane.<ref name=\":1\" /> She later became known as \"the Flying Countess\" for her many passenger journeys and then for flying in aircraft exhibitions across the UK and Ireland to raise money for the [[Royal Air Force]] during [[World War II]].<ref name=\"Tatler\">{{cite magazine|work=[[Tatler]]|title=A Flying Countess Who has Done Excellent Work on Behalf of R.A.F.|author=<!--Not given-->|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001852/19181218/014/0011|access-date=12 April 2020|url-access=subscription|page=11|date=18 December 1918}}</ref> She had also worked for aviation charities during [[World War I]], and was a guest at [[Edward Maitland (RAF officer)|Edward Maitland]]'s pre-flight celebrations of the [[R33-class airship#R34|R34]] successfully attempting the [[Transatlantic flight#First transatlantic flights|first return Atlantic crossing]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rosie|first=George|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gLO8BQAAQBAJ&pg=PT68&lpg=PT68&dq=Kathleen+Pelham+Burn&source=bl&ots=YzBWRUU8nu&sig=ACfU3U3eOJLB2zHs0qA3I8HY4Fik0fOK5A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi1x77Jnf_nAhU6QhUIHT8TC-04FBDoATABegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=Kathleen%20Pelham%20Burn&f=false|title=The Flight of the Titan: The Story of the R34|date=10 December 2012|publisher=Birlinn|isbn=978-0-85790-561-1}}</ref>\n\nHer other interests included driving fashionable cars around London and playing tennis at [[All England Lawn Tennis and Croquet Club]] (Wimbledon), being one of its first members.<ref name=\":1\" /> She competed in [[The Championships, Wimbledon]] once, in [[1914 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1914]], though she went out in the second round.<ref name=\"Wimbledon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/static/pdfs/archive/draws/1914_LS_A4.pdf|title=The Championships 1914: Ladies' All-Comers' Singles|website=[[The Championships, Wimbledon]]|access-date=12 April 2020|author=<!--No author-->}}</ref> She also played a lot of golf,<ref name=\":1\" /> and was a lover of contemporary art, but not music or literature.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBunbury notes that she held [[s\u00e9ance]]s that were social events, attended by celebrities of the day, including [[Jacob Epstein]], [[Augustus John]], and [[Wyndham Lewis]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1919 she was appointed [[Order of St Michael and St George|Companion, Order of St. Michael and St. George]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p25436.htm#c254359.1|title=Kathleen Pelham Burn|date=n.d.|website=thepeerage.com|url-status=live|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref> She was also a [[Order of the British Empire|Commander of the Order of the British Empire]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/drogheda1661.htm|title=Drogheda, Earl of (I, 1661)|website=cracroftspeerage.co.uk|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Walford|first=Edward|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TuHIDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA399&lpg=PA399&dq=Kathleen+Pelham-Burn+CBE&source=bl&ots=ca5k4B4KSs&sig=ACfU3U3HCBWxfiMh5dPZrhsCFDGfAAJ_3g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwju3-2Ysf_nAhUdQRUIHRugDY8Q6AEwA3oECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=Kathleen%20Pelham-Burn%20CBE&f=false|title=The county families of the United Kingdom; or, Royal manual of the titled and untitled aristocracy of England, Wales, Scotland, and Ireland|publisher=Dalcassian Publishing Company|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Kathleen Pelham Burns, cameo portrait LCCN2014683495 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|150px|Pelham Burn in 1909]]\nPelham Burn's first husband was the Anglo-Irish civil servant [[Henry Moore, 10th Earl of Drogheda|Henry Ponsonby Moore, 10th Earl of Drogheda]]. They wed on 3 March 1909 and divorced in 1922; Pelham Burn filed for divorce in 1921 on account of Henry's unfaithfulness. The marriage gave two children: [[Charles Moore, 11th Earl of Drogheda|Charles]] (born 1910) and Patricia (born 1912), whom Pelham Burn was granted custody of in the divorce.<ref name=\":3\" /> The couple had been married in \"a grand ceremony in [[St Giles' Cathedral|St. Giles's Cathedral]], Edinburgh\" and lived in London at 40 [[Wilton Crescent]];<ref name=\":1\" /> they also owned [[Moore Abbey]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.askaboutireland.ie/reading-room/history-heritage/big-houses-of-ireland/moore-abbey/20th-century/|title=20th Century|website=askaboutireland.ie|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref> Charles later said that his parents seemed to live separate lives and their divorce was not surprising.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn 31 August 1922, Pelham Burn married Guillermo \"Billy\" de Landa y Escandon, a Mexican playboy and son of former [[Mexico City]] Governor [[Guillermo Landa y Escand\u00f3n]]. They divorced in 1929.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nShe is accounted by her son as being [[bisexual]], as he wrote: \"All her life she was attracted by men and women [...] she knew intimately [[Donald Campbell]], [[Alan Cobham]], [[Kaye Don]], [[Jim Mollison]], [[Amy Johnson]], and plenty of others besides.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> She may have also had an affair with Wyndham Lewis during her first marriage,<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> whom she also commissioned for art against her husband's wishes.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|ie}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = Anne Tower Moir\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = [[Earl of Drogheda|Countess of Drogheda]]\n| years = 1909\u20131922\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = Olive Mary Paget\n}}\n{{