{"title_page": "George Herbert, 13th Earl of Pembroke", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Earl of Pembroke\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image =George Herbert Vanity Fair 14 July 1888.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption =\"The Earl and the Doctor\"<br>Herbert as caricatured by Ape ([[Carlo Pellegrini (caricaturist)|Carlo Pellegrini]]) in [[Vanity Fair (British magazine)|Vanity Fair]], July 1888\n| order1 = [[Under-Secretary of State for War]]\n| term_start1 = 2 March 1874 \n| term_end1 = 24 May 1875\n| monarch1 = [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Victoria]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Benjamin Disraeli]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Henry Petty-Fitzmaurice, 5th Marquess of Lansdowne|The Marquess of Lansdowne]]\n| successor1 = [[George Cadogan, 5th Earl Cadogan|The Earl Cadogan]]\n| birth_date = {{birth-date|6 July 1850|}} \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = {{death-date and age|3 May 1895|6 July 1850}} \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[British people|British]]\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]  \n| alma_mater = \n| spouse = Lady Gertrude Chetwynd-Talbot (1840-1906) \n}}\n\n'''George Robert Charles Herbert, 13th Earl of Pembroke, 10th Earl of Montgomery''' (6 July 1850 \u2013 3 May 1895), known as '''The Lord Herbert of Lea''' from 1861 to 1862, was a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician. He was [[Under-Secretary of State for War]] under [[Benjamin Disraeli]] between 1874 and 1875.\n\n==Background==\nPembroke was the eldest son of [[Sidney Herbert, 1st Baron Herbert of Lea]], only son of [[George Augustus Herbert, 11th Earl of Pembroke]], by his second wife [[Catherine Vorontsov|Catherine (n\u00e9e Countess Woronzow)]].<ref name=Vorontsov>[http://humphrysfamilytree.com/Herbert/woronzow.html Woronzow], HumphrysFamilyTree, accessed April 4, 2012</ref>  His mother was [[Elizabeth Herbert, Baroness Herbert of Lea]], daughter of Lieutenant-General Charles Ashe A'Court. He succeeded his father in the barony of Herbert of Lea in 1861 and the following year he inherited the earldom of Pembroke on the death of his uncle.<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\">{{cite web |url=http://thepeerage.com/p1277.htm#i12768 |work=The Peerage |title=George Robert Charles Herbert, 13th Earl of Pembroke |date=10 May 2003 }}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nPembroke served as [[Under-Secretary of State for War]] from 1874 to 1875 in the second [[Conservative Government 1874-1880|Conservative administration]] of [[Benjamin Disraeli]].<ref>Kidd, Charles, Williamson, David (editors). ''Debrett's Peerage and Baronetage'' (1990 edition). New York: St Martin's Press, 1990, {{Page needed |date=February 2013}}</ref>\n\nLord Pembroke never accepted office again, and rarely spoke in the [[House of Lords]], but he continued to take a keen interest in public affairs, both imperial and domestic, and communicated his views, through various periodicals and by speeches in the country, upon Ireland, the land question, imperial defence, and the navy. \nHe took a leading part in the volunteer movement, holding a commission for upwards of twenty years, and commanding the South Wilts battalion until within a few months of his death. \nHe believed firmly in the advantage of technical instruction, and gave practical proof thereof by building and endowing the Pembroke technical school near [[Dublin]]. \nLord Pembroke was a good sportsman, having been first a master of harriers for many years, and later of foxhounds; but a bad fall put an end to his hunting, and latterly he spent much of his time afloat, yachting and boat-sailing.<ref>{{DNBSupp|wstitle=Herbert, George Robert Charles |first=Herbert Eustace |last=Maxwell}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nLord Pembroke married Lady Gertrude Frances, daughter of [[Henry Chetwynd-Talbot, 18th Earl of Shrewsbury]], in 1874. He died in [[Frankfurt]] on 3 May 1895, aged 44, and was succeeded in his titles by his younger brother the Honourable [[Sidney Herbert, 14th Earl of Pembroke|Sidney Herbert]]. The Countess of Pembroke died in September 1906, aged 66.<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Ellenberger, Nancy W. ''Balfour's World: Aristocracy and Political Culture at the Fin de Si\u00e8cle'' (2015). [https://www.amazon.com/Balfours-World-Aristocracy-Political-Culture/dp/1783270373/ excerpt]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box \n | title  = [[Under-Secretary of State for War]]\n | years  = 1874\u20131875\n | before = [[Henry Petty-Fitzmaurice, 5th Marquess of Lansdowne|The Marquess of Lansdowne]]\n | after  = [[George Cadogan, 5th Earl Cadogan|The Earl Cadogan]]}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Baron Herbert of Lea]]\n | years  = 1861\u20131895\n | before = [[Sidney Herbert, 1st Baron Herbert of Lea|Sidney Herbert]]\n | after  = [[Sidney Herbert, 14th Earl of Pembroke|Sidney Herbert]]}}\n{{s-reg|en}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Earl of Pembroke]] \n | years  = 1862\u20131895\n | before = [[Robert Herbert, 12th Earl of Pembroke|Robert Henry Herbert]]\n | after  = [[Sidney Herbert, 14th Earl of Pembroke|Sidney Herbert]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pembroke, George Herbert, 13th Earl of}}\n[[Category:1850 births]]\n[[Category:1895 deaths]]\n[[Category:Herbert family|George Herbert, 13th Earl of Pembroke]]\n[[Category:Earls of Pembroke (1551)|George]]\n[[Category:Earls of Montgomery|George]]\n[[Category:Earls in the Peerage of England]]\n[[Category:British people of Russian descent]]\n[[Category:Members of Wiltshire County Council]]\n[[Category:Eldest sons of barons]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Earl of Pembroke\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image =George Herbert Vanity Fair 14 July 1888.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption =\"The Earl and the Doctor\"<br>Herbert as caricatured by Ape ([[Carlo Pellegrini (caricaturist)|Carlo Pellegrini]]) in [[Vanity Fair (British magazine)|Vanity Fair]], July 1888\n| order1 = [[Under-Secretary of State for War]]\n| term_start1 = 2 March 1874 \n| term_end1 = 24 May 1875\n| monarch1 = [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Victoria]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Benjamin Disraeli]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Henry Petty-Fitzmaurice, 5th Marquess of Lansdowne|The Marquess of Lansdowne]]\n| successor1 = [[George Cadogan, 5th Earl Cadogan|The Earl Cadogan]]\n| birth_date = {{birth-date|6 July 1850|}} \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = {{death-date and age|3 May 1895|6 July 1850}} \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[British people|British]]\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]  \n| alma_mater = \n| spouse = Lady Gertrude Chetwynd-Talbot (1840-1906) \n}}\n\n'''George Robert Charles Herbert, 13th Earl of Pembroke, 10th Earl of Montgomery''' (6 July 1850 \u2013 3 May 1895), known as '''The Lord Herbert of Lea''' from 1861 to 1862, was a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician. He was [[Under-Secretary of State for War]] under [[Benjamin Disraeli]] between 1874 and 1875.\n\n==Background==\nPembroke was the eldest son of [[Sidney Herbert, 1st Baron Herbert of Lea]], only son of [[George Augustus Herbert, 11th Earl of Pembroke]], by his second wife [[Catherine Vorontsov|Catherine (n\u00e9e Countess Woronzow)]].<ref name=Vorontsov>[http://humphrysfamilytree.com/Herbert/woronzow.html Woronzow], HumphrysFamilyTree, accessed April 4, 2012</ref>  His mother was [[Elizabeth Herbert, Baroness Herbert of Lea]], daughter of Lieutenant-General Charles Ashe A'Court. He succeeded his father in the barony of Herbert of Lea in 1861 and the following year he inherited the earldom of Pembroke on the death of his uncle.<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\">{{cite web |url=http://thepeerage.com/p1277.htm#i12768 |work=The Peerage |title=George Robert Charles Herbert, 13th Earl of Pembroke |date=10 May 2003 }}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nPembroke served as [[Under-Secretary of State for War]] from 1874 to 1875 in the second [[Conservative Government 1874-1880|Conservative administration]] of [[Benjamin Disraeli]].<ref>Kidd, Charles, Williamson, David (editors). ''Debrett's Peerage and Baronetage'' (1990 edition). New York: St Martin's Press, 1990, {{Page needed |date=February 2013}}</ref>\n\nLord Pembroke never accepted office again, and rarely spoke in the [[House of Lords]], but he continued to take a keen interest in public affairs, both imperial and domestic, and communicated his views, through various periodicals and by speeches in the country, upon Ireland, the land question, imperial defence, and the navy. \nHe took a leading part in the volunteer movement, holding a commission for upwards of twenty years, and commanding the South Wilts battalion until within a few months of his death. \nHe believed firmly in the advantage of technical instruction, and gave practical proof thereof by building and endowing the Pembroke technical school near [[Dublin]]. \nLord Pembroke was a good sportsman, having been first a master of harriers for many years, and later of foxhounds ; but a bad fall put an end to his hunting, and latterly he spent much of his time afloat, yachting and boat-sailing.<ref>{{DNBSupp|wstitle=Herbert, George Robert Charles |first=Herbert Eustace |last=Maxwell}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nLord Pembroke married Lady Gertrude Frances, daughter of [[Henry Chetwynd-Talbot, 18th Earl of Shrewsbury]], in 1874. He died in [[Frankfurt]] on 3 May 1895, aged 44, and was succeeded in his titles by his younger brother the Honourable [[Sidney Herbert, 14th Earl of Pembroke|Sidney Herbert]]. The Countess of Pembroke died in September 1906, aged 66.<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Ellenberger, Nancy W. ''Balfour's World: Aristocracy and Political Culture at the Fin de Si\u00e8cle'' (2015). [https://www.amazon.com/Balfours-World-Aristocracy-Political-Culture/dp/