e and Legend (updated and revised) |publisher=[[OR Books]] |year=2015 |isbn=978-1-939293-96-1 |location=New York}}\n* {{cite book |last=Mercer |first=Jane |title=Great Lovers of the Movies |publisher=Crescent Books |year=1975 |isbn=0-517-13126-9 |location=New York |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/greatloversofmov0000merc }}\n* {{cite book |last=Munn |first=Michael |title=Clint Eastwood: Hollywood's Loner |publisher=Robson |year=1992 |location=London |isbn=978-0-86051-790-0}}\n* {{cite book |author=Oates, Bob |title=Celebrating the Dawn: Maharishi Mahesh Yogi and the TM Technique |publisher=Putnam |year=1976 |isbn=0-399-11815-2 |location=New York}}\n* {{cite book |last=O'Brien |first=Daniel |title=Clint Eastwood: Film-Maker |publisher=B.T. Batsford |year=1996 |isbn=0-7134-7839-X |location=London |url=https://archive.org/details/clinteastwood00dani}}\n* {{cite book |author=Ivy Press |title=Heritage Vintage Movie Poster Signature Auction 2005 Catalog #624 |year=2005 |publisher=Heritage Capital Corporation |isbn=978-1-59967-004-1}}\n* {{cite book |last=Roberts |first=James B. |last2=Skutt |first2=Alexander |title=The Boxing Register: International Boxing Hall of Fame Official Record Book |publisher=McBooks Press |year=2006 |isbn=1-59013-121-5 |location=Ithaca, NY}}\n* {{cite book |last=Rogin |first=Michael Paul |title=Ronald Reagan, the Movie and Other Episodes in Political Demonology |year=1988 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=978-0-520-06469-0}}\n* {{cite book |last=Schickel |first=Richard |title=Clint Eastwood: A Biography |publisher=Knopf |year=1996 |isbn=978-0-679-42974-6 |location=New York |url=https://archive.org/details/clinteastwoodbio00schi}}\n* {{cite book |last=Slocum |first=J. David |title=Violence and American Cinema |work=AFI film readers |publisher=Routledge |year=2001 |isbn=0-415-92810-9 |location=New York}}\n* {{cite book |last=Smith |first=Paul |title=Clint Eastwood: A Cultural Production: Volume 8 of American Culture |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |year=1993 |isbn=0-8166-1960-3 |location=Minneapolis}}\n* {{cite book |year=2004 |chapter=Action Movie Hysteria of Eastwood Bound |title=Stars: The Film Reader |publisher=Routledge |isbn=0-415-27893-7 |location=London |last=Smith |first=Paul |editor-last=Fischer |editor-first=Lucy |editor-last2=Landy |editor-first2=Marcia}}\n* {{cite book |last=Stillman |first=Deanne |title=Getting Back at Dad |year=1981 |publisher=Wideview Books |isbn=978-0-87223-725-4}}\n* {{cite book |last=Sweeney |first=Patrick |title=The Gun Digest Book of Smith & Wesson |year=2004 |publisher=Gun Digest Books |isbn=978-0-87349-792-3}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Verlhac |first1=Pierre-Henri |last2=Bogdanovich |first2=Peter |title=Clint Eastwood: A Life in Pictures |year=2008 |publisher=Chronicle Books |isbn=978-0-8118-6154-0}}\n* {{cite book |last=Zmijewsky |first=Boris |author2=Lee Pfeiffer |title=The Films of Clint Eastwood |publisher=Citadel Press |year=1982 |isbn=0-8065-0863-9 |location=Secaucus, NJ}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Cornell |first=Drucilla |title=Clint Eastwood and Issues of American Masculinity |year=2009 |publisher=Fordham University Press |isbn=978-0-8232-3013-6}}\n* {{cite book |last=Engel |first=Leonard |title=Clint Eastwood, Actor and Director: New Perspectives |publisher=[[University of Utah Press]] |year=2007 |isbn=978-0-87480-900-8 |location=Salt Lake City |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/clinteastwoodact0000unse }}\n* {{cite book |last=Gabbard |first=Glen O. |title=Psychoanalysis and Film |work=International Journal of Psychoanalysis Key Papers Series |publisher=Karnac Books |year=2001 |isbn=1-85575-275-1 |location=London; New York}}\n* {{cite book |last=Grunert |first=Andrea |title=Dictionnaire Clint Eastwood |publisher=Vend\u00e9miaire |year=2016 |isbn=978-2-36358-243-0 |location=Paris}}\n* {{cite book |last=Johnstone |first=Iain |title=The Man with No Name: The Biography of Clint Eastwood |publisher=Plexus |year=2007 |isbn=978-0-85965-026-7 |location=London}}\n* {{cite book |last=Thompson |first=Douglas |title=Clint Eastwood: Billion Dollar Man |publisher=John Blake |year=2005 |isbn=978-1-85782-572-5 |location=London}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{sisterlinks|collapsible=true|b=no|s=no|v=no|n=no|wikt=no|voy=no|species=no|d=Q43203}}\n* {{Britannica|177481}}\n* {{IMDb name|142}}\n* {{C-SPAN|clinteastwood}}\n* {{Charlie Rose view|115}}\n* {{Guardian topic}}\n* {{NYTtopic|people/e/clint_eastwood}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes person|clint_eastwood}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n* {{Worldcat id|lccn-n50-24426}}\n* [https://articles.latimes.com/keyword/clint-eastwood Clint Eastwood] collected news and commentary at the ''Los Angeles Times''\n\n{{Clint Eastwood}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Clint Eastwood|Awards for Clint Eastwood]]\n| list =\n{{Academy Award Best Director}}\n{{AFI Life Achievement Award}}\n{{British Film Institute Fellowship}}\n{{BAFTA Los Angeles Britannia Awards}}\n{{Cecil B. DeMille Award 1976\u20132000}}\n{{David O. Selznick Achievement Award in Theatrical Motion Pictures}}\n{{DirectorsGuildofAmericaAwardFeatureFilm}}\n{{DirectorsGuildofAmericaAwardLifetimeFilm}}\n{{Lincoln Center Gala Tribute}}\n{{Golden Globe Award for Best Director 1966\u20131990}}\n{{Hasty Pudding Man of the Year}}\n{{Honorary C\u00e9sar}}\n{{Thalberg Award}}\n{{Kennedy Center Honorees 2000s}}\n{{Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Director}}\n{{National Board of Review Award for Best Actor}}\n{{National Board of Review Award for Best Director}}\n{{National Medal of Arts recipients 2000s}}\n{{National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Director}}\n{{New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Director}}\n{{People's Choice Award for Favorite Movie Actor}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Director}}\n{{Screen Actors Guild Lifetime Achievement Award}}\n{{Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Director}}\n}}\n{{Cannes Film Festival jury presidents}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eastwood, Clint}}\n[[Category:Clint Eastwood|*]]\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:AFI Life Achievement Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Akira Kurosawa Award winners]]\n[[Category:American aviators]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American film score composers]]\n[[Category:American investors]]\n[[Category:American jazz composers]]\n[[Category:American libertarians]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:American philanthropists]]\n[[Category:American real estate businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American restaurateurs]]\n[[Category:Best Directing Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Director Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:California Independents]]\n[[Category:California Libertarians]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n[[Category:Cecil B. DeMille Award Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:C\u00e9sar Honorary Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Commandeurs of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Directors Guild of America Award winners]]\n[[Category:Eastwood family]]\n[[Category:American actor-politicians]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:Fellini Gold Medalists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n[[Category:Film directors from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Film producers from California]]\n[[Category:Helicopter pilots]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Kennedy Center honorees]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles City College alumni]]\n[[Category:Male actors from California]]\n[[Category:Male actors from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:People from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Male actors from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Male film score composers]]\n[[Category:Male jazz composers]]\n[[Category:Male Spaghetti Western actors]]\n[[Category:Male Western (genre) film actors]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in California]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from California]]\n[[Category:Mountaineering film directors]]\n[[Category:Musicians from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Musicians from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Non-interventionism]]\n[[Category:People from Carmel-by-the-Sea, California]]\n[[Category:People from Pebble Beach, California]]\n[[Category:People from Piedmont, California]]\n[[Category:Producers who won the Best Picture Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Rising Sun, 3rd class]]\n[[Category:Screen Actors Guild Life Achievement Award]]\n[[Category:Seattle University alumni]]\n[[Category:Transcendental Meditation practitioners]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:United States National Medal of Arts recipients]]\n[[Category:Western (genre) film directors]]\n[[Category:Western (genre) television actors]]\n[[Category:People from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript| Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clint_Eastwood"}
{"title_page": "Red River War", "text_new": "{{hatnote|Red River War may also refer to the conflict between Oklahoma and Texas known as the [[Red River Bridge War]].}}\n\n{{Infobox Military Conflict\n| conflict    = Red River War\n\n| partof      = the [[American Indian Wars]]\n| date        = 1874\u201375\n| place       = Southern Plains\n| result      = United States Victory-End of the [[Texas\u2013Indian wars]]\n| territory   = \n| image       = Ledger-sm2.jpg\n| image_size  = 300px\n| caption     = A Kiowa [[ledger art|ledger drawing]] possibly depicting the [[Billy Dixon#Battle of Buffalo Wallow|Buffalo Wallow battle]] in 1874, one of several clashes between Southern Plains Indians and the U.S. Army during the Red River War.\n| combatant1  = {{flag|United States|1867|size=25px}}\n| combatant2  = {{flagicon image|Flag of Northern Cheyenne.svg|size=25px}} [[Cheyenne]]<br/>{{flagicon image|Flag of Arapaho Nation.svg|size=25px}} [[Arapaho]]<br/>{{flagicon image|Flag of the Comanche Nation.svg|size=25px}} [[Comanche]]<br/>[[Kiowa]]\n| commander1  = \n| commander2  = \n| strength1   = \n| strength2   = \n| casualties1 = \n| casualties2 = \n}}\n\nThe '''Red River War''' was a military campaign launched by the [[United States Army]] in 1874 to displace the [[Comanche]], [[Kiowa]], [[Southern Cheyenne]], and [[Arapaho]] Native American tribes from the [[Southern Plains]], and forcibly relocate the tribes to reservations in [[Indian Territory]]. Lasting only a few months, the war had several army columns crisscross the [[Texas Panhandle]] in an effort to locate, harass, and capture highly mobile Native American bands. Most of the engagements were small skirmishes in which neither side suffered many casualties. The war wound down over the last few months of 1874, as fewer and fewer Indian bands had the strength and supplies to remain in the field. Though the last significantly sized group did not surrender until mid-1875, the war marked the end of free-roaming Indian populations on the southern Great Plains.\n\n==Background==\n[[Image:Map of the Great Plains.png|thumb|300px|right|Region of the Great Plains in North America]]\nPrior to the arrival of [[English American]] settlers on the [[Great Plains]], the southern Plains tribes had evolved into a nomadic pattern of existence. Beginning in the 1830s, significant numbers of permanent settlements were established in what had previously been the exclusive territory of the [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas]]. Attacks, raids, and counter-raids occurred frequently. Prior to the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], the U.S. Army was only sporadically involved in these frontier conflicts, manning forts, but limited to a handful of larger expeditions due to manpower limitations. During the Civil War, the Regular Army withdrew almost completely, and Indian raids increased dramatically. Texas, as part of the [[Confederate States of America]], lacked the military resources to fight both the Union and the tribes.<ref>Gwynne, S.C. 2010, ''Empire of the Summer Moon: Quanah Parker and the Rise and Fall of the Comanches, the Most Powerful Indian Tribe in American History'', p. 207-221</ref>\n \nAfter the war, the military began reasserting itself along the frontier. The [[Medicine Lodge Treaty]], signed near present-day Medicine Lodge, Kansas, in 1867, called for two reservations to be set aside in Indian Territory, one for the Comanche and Kiowa and one for the Southern Cheyenne and Arapaho. According to the treaty, the government would provide the tribes with housing, agricultural training, and food and other supplies. In exchange, the Indians agreed to cease raiding and attacking settlements. Dozens of chiefs endorsed the treaty and some tribal members moved voluntarily to the reservations, but it was never officially ratified and several groups of Indians still on the Plains did not attend the negotiations.\n \nIn 1870, a new technique for tanning [[American bison|buffalo]] hides became commercially available.<ref>Cronon, William. \"Nature's Metropolis\". W. W. Norton & Company, 1992, p. 216</ref> In response, commercial hunters began systematically targeting buffalo for the first time. Once numbering in the tens of millions, the buffalo population plummeted. By 1878, they were all but extinct.\n \nThe destruction of the buffalo herds was a disaster for the Plains Indians, on and off the reservations. The entire nomadic way of life had been based around the animals. They were used for food, fuel, and construction materials. Without abundant buffalo, the southern Plains Indians had no means of self-support.\n \nBy the winter of 1873-1874, the southern Plains Indians were in crisis. The reduction of the buffalo herds combined with increasing numbers of new settlers and more aggressive military patrols had put them in an unsustainable position.\n\n==War==\nDuring the winter, a spiritual leader named [[Isa-tai]] emerged among the Quahadi Band of Comanches. Isa-tai claimed to have the power to render himself and others invulnerable to their enemies, including to bullets, and was able to rally an enormous number of Indians for large raids. Also, a shift occurred within the political structure of the Kiowa, bringing the war faction (influenced by the head chief [[Lone Wolf the Elder|Guipago]], or Gunnjsnnjkdsv nks; vkn;svskje.nvefskjb typoi-pah-gho, sometimes known, by modern people, as Lone Wolf \"the Elder\" to prevent confusion with Mamay-dayte, later named [[Lone Wolf the Younger|Lone Wolf \"the Younger\"]]) into a greater position of influence than they had held previously.\n \n===Early engagements===\n{{Main|Second Battle of Adobe Walls}}\n[[File:Captain Pratt Native Americans.jpg|thumb|left|Native American prisoners of the Red River War, [[Fort Marion]], Florida 1875: The inscription on the back of the original stereograph says: L to R:[[Lone Wolf the Elder|Lone Wolf]], Double Vision, [[White Horse (chief)|White Horse]], [[Woman's Heart]], [[Mamante (Owl Prophet)]] - Kiowas. Officer left is Capt. [[Richard Henry Pratt|Richard H. Pratt]]]]\n\nOn 27 June 1874, Isa-tai and Comanche chief [[Quanah Parker]] led about 250 warriors in an attack on a small outpost of buffalo hunters in the [[Texas Panhandle]] called [[Adobe Walls, Texas|Adobe Walls]]. The encampment consisted of just a few buildings and was occupied by only 28 men and one woman. Though a few whites were killed in the opening moments of the Second Battle of Adobe Walls (the first had been [[First Battle of Adobe Walls|in 1864]]), the majority was able to barricade themselves indoors and hold off the attack. Using large-caliber buffalo guns, the hunters could fire on the warriors from much greater range than the Indians had expected, and the attack failed.<ref>Gwynne, S.C. 2010, ''Empire of the Summer Moon: Quanah Parker and the Rise and Fall of the Comanches, the Most Powerful Indian Tribe in American History'', p. 267-271</ref>\n \nA second engagement involving the Kiowa took place in Texas. Warriors led by Lone Wolf attacked a patrol of Texas Rangers in July. The Lost Valley fight had light casualties on both sides, but it served to raise tensions along the frontier and push the Army into an aggressive response.\n \nThe explosion of violence took the government by surprise. The \"peace policy\" of the Grant administration was deemed a failure, and the Army was authorized to subdue the southern Plains tribes with whatever force necessary. At this time, roughly 1,800 Cheyennes, 2,000 Comanches, and 1,000 Kiowas remained at large. Combined, they mounted about 1,200 warriors.<ref>Utley, Robert M. 1973, ''Frontier Regulars the United States Army and the Indian, 1866-1891'' [https://www.questia.com/library/book/frontier-regulars-the-united-states-army-and-the-indian-1866-1891-by-robert-m-utley.jsp online edition]\n p 211</ref>\n\n===Army response===\n[[File:Texas Panhandle.PNG|thumb|Area comprising locations of the battles in the Texas Panhandle]]\n\nGeneral [[Phillip Sheridan]] ordered five army columns to converge on the general area of the Texas Panhandle and specifically upon the upper tributaries of the [[Red River of the South|Red River]]. The strategy was to deny the Indians any safe haven and attack them unceasingly until they went permanently to the reservations.\n \nThree of the five columns were under the command of Colonel [[Ranald S. Mackenzie]]. The [[10th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|Tenth Cavalry]], under Lieutenant Colonel John W. Davidson, came due west from [[Fort Sill]]. The [[11th Infantry Regiment (United States)|Eleventh Infantry]], under Lieutenant Colonel [[George P. Buell]], moved northwest from [[Fort Griffin]]. Mackenzie himself led the [[4th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|Fourth Cavalry]] north from [[Fort Concho]].\n \nThe fourth column, consisting of the [[6th Cavalry Regiment|Sixth Cavalry]] and [[5th Infantry Regiment (United States)|Fifth Infantry]], was commanded by Colonel [[Nelson A. Miles]] and came south from [[Fort Dodge (US Army Post)|Fort Dodge]]. The fifth column, the [[8th Cavalry Regiment|Eighth Cavalry]] commanded by Major William R. Price, a total of 225 officers and men, plus six Indian scouts and two guides originated from [[Fort Union National Monument|Fort Union]],<ref>Leo E. Oliva: ''Fort Union and the Frontier Army in the Southwest \u2212 A Historic Resource Study''. Division of History \u2212 National Park Service, Santa Fe, New Mexico 1993, [http://www.nps.gov/history/history/online_books/foun/chap7.htm chapter 7]</ref> marched east via [[Fort Bascom]] in New Mexico.<ref>Gwynne, S.C. 2010 ''Empire of the Summer Moon: Quanah Parker and the Rise and Fall of the Comanches, the Most Powerful Indian Tribe in American History'' p. 275-276</ref> The plan called for the converging columns to maintain a continuous offensive until a decisive defeat had been inflicted on the Indians.\n \nAs many as 20 engagements took place across the Texas Panhandle. The Army, consisting entirely of soldiers and scouts, sought to engage the Indians at any opportunity. The Indians, traveling with women, children, and elderly, mostly attempted to avoid them. When the two did encounter one another, the Indians usually tried to escape before the Army could force them to surrender. However, even a successful escape could be disastrously costly if horses, food, and equipment had to be left behind. By contrast, the Army and its Indian scouts had access to essentially limitless supplies and equipment, they frequently burned anything they captured from retreating Indians, and were capable of continuing operations indefinitely. The war continued throughout the fall of 1874, but increasing numbers of Indians were forced to give up and head for Fort Sill to enter the reservation system.\n\n===Battle of Palo Duro Canyon===\n{{Main|Battle of Palo Duro Canyon}}\n[[File:Palo Duro 2002.jpg|thumb|Rugged terrain of the [[Palo Duro Canyon]]]]\nEarly in September, [[Black Seminole Scouts]] in advance of the 4th Cavalry were ambushed by Comanche near the [[Llano Estacado|Staked Plains]] and escaped with their lives. The scouts relayed the Comanche position and put Mackenzie on alert.<ref>{{cite book|last=Schubert|first=Frank N.|title=Black Valor: Buffalo Soldiers and the Medal of Honor, 1870-1898|publisher=Scholarly Resources Inc.|authorlink=Frank N. Schubert|p=[https://archive.org/details/blackvalorbuffal00schu/page/33 33]|date=1997|isbn=9780842025867|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/blackvalorbuffal00schu/page/33}}</ref>\n\nThe largest Army victory came when Mackenzie's scouts found a large village of Comanche, Kiowa, and Cheyenne, including their horses and winter food supply, in upper Palo Duro Canyon. At dawn on September 28, Mackenzie's troops attacked down a steep canyon wall. The Indians were caught by surprise and did not have time to gather their horses or supplies before retreating. Sergeant John Charlton wrote of the battle:\n \n<blockquote>The warriors held their ground for a time, fighting desperately to cover the exit of their squaws and pack animals, but under the persistent fire of the troops, they soon began falling back.<ref>Gwynne, S.C. 2010 ''Empire of the Summer Moon: Quanah Parker and the Rise and Fall of the Comanches, the Most Powerful Indian Tribe in American History'', p. 281</ref></blockquote>\n \nOnly four Indians were killed, but the loss was devastating. Mackenzie's men burned over 450 lodges and destroyed countless pounds of buffalo meat. They also took 1,400 horses, most of which were subsequently shot to prevent the Indians from recapturing them.\n \nExcept for its unusually large size, the Battle of Palo Duro Canyon was typical of the war. Most encounters produced few or no casualties, but the Indians could not afford the constant loss of food and mounts. Even if it escaped immediate danger, an Indian band that found itself on foot and out of food generally had no choice but to give up and head for the reservation.\n\n==Aftermath==\n\nThe Red River War officially ended in June 1875 when Quanah Parker and his band of Quahadi Comanche entered Fort Sill and surrendered; they were the last large roaming band of southwestern Indians. Combined with the extermination of the buffalo, the war left the Texas Panhandle permanently open to settlement by farmers and ranchers.<ref>Utley, Robert M. 1973, Frontier Regulars the United States Army and the Indian, 1866-1891 online edition, p. 211</ref><ref>Haley, James. L. 2009 ''The Red River War'' in ''Handbook of Texas Online'' [http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/qdr02 online]\n</ref> It was the final military defeat of the once powerful Southern Plains tribes and brought an end to the [[Texas\u2013Indian Wars]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Carter, R.G., On the Border with Mackenzie, 1935, Washington D.C.: Enyon Printing Co. {{ISBN|978-0-87611-246-5}}\n* Hutton, Paul. ''Phil Sheridan and His Army'' (1985).\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/lakota_sioux_and_comanche_indians/11627582825/ Map of Red River War 1874-75]\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.texasbeyondhistory.net/redriver/ |title=Red River War |website=Texas Beyond History |publisher=University of Texas at Austin}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.pan-tex.net/usr/p/pampa-hist/red.htm |title=Red River Wars |website=History of Pampa, Gray County, Texas |publisher=Pampa Cyber Net}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.thc.state.tx.us/public/upload/publications/red-river-war.pdf |title=Red River War of 1874-1875 ~ Clash of Cultures in the Texas Panhandle |website=Texas Travel Guide |publisher=Texas Historical Commission}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/qdr02 |title=Red River War |last=Haley |first=James L. |website=TSHA Handbook of Texas Online |publisher=Texas State Historical Association}}\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1874]]\n[[Category:1874 in the United States]]\n[[Category:Comanche tribe]]\n[[Category:Cheyenne tribe]]\n[[Category:Indian wars of the American Old West]]\n[[Category:Comanche Campaign]]\n[[Category:Wars between the United States and Native Americans]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Comanche]]\n[[Category:Presidency of Ulysses S. Grant]]\n[[Category:Red River of the South]]\n", "text_old": "{{hatnote|Red River War may also refer to the conflict between Oklahoma and Texas known as the [[Red River Bridge War]].}}\n\n{{Infobox Military Conflict\n| conflict    = Red River War\n\n| partof      = the [[American Indian Wars]]\n| date        = 1874\u201375\n| place       = Southern Plains\n| result      = United States Victory-End of the [[Texas\u2013Indian wars]]\n| territory   = \n| image       = Ledger-sm2.jpg\n| image_size  = 300px\n| caption     = A Kiowa [[ledger art|ledger drawing]] possibly depicting the [[Billy Dixon#Battle of Buffalo Wallow|Buffalo Wallow battle]] in 1874, one of several clashes between Southern Plains Indians and the U.S. Army during the Red River War.\n| combatant1  = {{flag|United States|1867|size=25px}}\n| combatant2  = {{flagicon image|Flag of Northern Cheyenne.svg|size=25px}} [[Cheyenne]]<br/>{{flagicon image|Flag of Arapaho Nation.svg|size=25px}} [[Arapaho]]<br/>{{flagicon image|Flag of the Comanche Nation.svg|size=25px}} [[Comanche]]<br/>[[Kiowa]]\n| commander1  = \n| commander2  = \n| strength1   = \n| strength2   = \n| casualties1 = \n| casualties2 = \n}}\n\nThe '''Red River War''' was a military campaign launched by the [[United States Army]] in 1874 to displace the [[Comanche]], [[Kiowa]], [[Southern Cheyenne]], and [[Arapaho]] Native American tribes from the [[Southern Plains]], and forcibly relocate the tribes to reservations in [[Indian Territory]]. Lasting only a few months, the war had several army columns crisscross the [[Texas Panhandle]] in an effort to locate, harass, and capture highly mobile Native American bands. Most of the engagements were small skirmishes in which neither side suffered many casualties. The war wound down over the last few months of 1874, as fewer and fewer Indian bands had the strength and supplies to remain in the field. Though the last significantly sized group did not surrender until mid-1875, the war marked the end of free-roaming Indian populations on the southern Great Plains.\n\n==Background==\n[[Image:Map of the Great Plains.png|thumb|300px|right|Region of the Great Plains in North America]]\nPrior to the arrival of [[English American]] settlers on the [[Great Plains]], the southern Plains tribes had evolved into a nomadic pattern of existence. Beginning in the 1830s, significant numbers of permanent settlements were established in what had previously been the exclusive territory of the [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas]]. Attacks, raids, and counter-raids occurred frequently. Prior to the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], the U.S. Army was only sporadically involved in these frontier conflicts, manning forts, but limited to a handful of larger expeditions due to manpower limitations. During the Civil War, the Regular Army withdrew almost completely, and Indian raids increased dramatically. Texas, as part of the [[Confederate States of America]], lacked the military resources to fight both the Union and the tribes.<ref>Gwynne, S.C. 2010, ''Empire of the Summer Moon: Quanah Parker and the Rise and Fall of the Comanches, the Most Powerful Indian Tribe in American History'', p. 207-221</ref>\n \nAfter the war, the military began reasserting itself along the frontier. The [[Medicine Lodge Treaty]], signed near present-day Medicine Lodge, Kansas, in 1867, called for two reservations to be set aside in Indian Territory, one for the Comanche and Kiowa and one for the Southern Cheyenne and Arapaho. According to the treaty, the government would provide the tribes with housing, agricultural training, and food and other supplies. In exchange, the Indians agreed to cease raiding and attacking settlements. Dozens of chiefs endorsed the treaty and some tribal members moved voluntarily to the reservations, but it was never officially ratified and several groups of Indians still on the Plains did not attend the negotiations.\n \nIn 1870, a new technique for tanning [[American bison|buffalo]] hides became commercially available.<ref>Cronon, William. \"Nature's Metropolis\". W. W. Norton & Company, 1992, p. 216</ref> In response, commercial hunters began systematically targeting buffalo for the first time. Once numbering in the tens of millions, the buffalo population plummeted. By 1878, they were all but extinct.\n \nThe destruction of the buffalo herds was a disaster for the Plains Indians, on and off the reservations. The entire nomadic way of life had been based around the animals. They were used for food, fuel, and construction materials. Without abundant buffalo, the southern Plains Indians had no means of self-support.\n \nBy the winter of 1873-1874, the southern Plains Indians were in crisis. The reduction of the buffalo herds combined with increasing numbers of new settlers and more aggressive military patrols had put them in an unsustainable position.\n\n==War==\nDuring the winter, a spiritual leader named [[Isa-tai]] emerged among the Quahadi Band of Comanches. Isa-tai claimed to have the power to render himself and others invulnerable to their enemies, including to bullets, and was able to rally an enormous number of Indians for large raids. Also, a shift occurred within the political structure of the Kiowa, bringing the war faction (influenced by the head chief [[Lone Wolf the Elder|Guipago]], or Gui-pah-gho, sometimes known, by modern people, as Lone Wolf \"the Elder\" to prevent confusion with Mamay-dayte, later named [[Lone Wolf the Younger|Lone Wolf \"the Younger\"]]) into a greater position of influence than they had held previously.\n \n===Early engagements===\n{{Main|Second Battle of Adobe Walls}}\n[[File:Captain Pratt Native Americans.jpg|thumb|left|Native American prisoners of the Red River War, [[Fort Marion]], Florida 1875: The inscription on the back of the original stereograph says: L to R:[[Lone Wolf the Elder|Lone Wolf]], Double Vision, [[White Horse (chief)|White Horse]], [[Woman's Heart]], [[Mamante (Owl Prophet)]] - Kiowas. Officer left is Capt. [[Richard Henry Pratt|Richard H. Pratt]]]]\n\nOn 27 June 1874, Isa-tai and Comanche chief [[Quanah Parker]] led about 250 warriors in an attack on a small outpost of buffalo hunters in the [[Texas Panhandle]] called [[Adobe Walls, Texas|Adobe Walls]]. The encampment consisted of just a few buildings and was occupied by only 28 men and one woman. Though a few whites were killed in the opening moments of the Second Battle of Adobe Walls (the first had been [[First Battle of Adobe Walls|in 1864]]), the majority was able to barricade themselves indoors and hold off the attack. Using large-caliber buffalo guns, the hunters could fire on the warriors from much greater range than the Indians had expected, and the attack failed.<ref>Gwynne, S.C. 2010, ''Empire of the Summer Moon: Quanah Parker and the Rise and Fall of the Comanches, the Most Powerful Indian Tribe in American History'', p. 267-271</ref>\n \nA second engagement involving the Kiowa took place in Texas. Warriors led by Lone Wolf attacked a patrol of Texas Rangers in July. The Lost Valley fight had light casualties on both sides, but it served to raise tensions along the frontier and push the Army into an aggressive response.\n \nThe explosion of violence took the government by surprise. The \"peace policy\" of the Grant administration was deemed a failure, and the Army was authorized to subdue the southern Plains tribes with whatever force necessary. At this time, roughly 1,800 Cheyennes, 2,000 Comanches, and 1,000 Kiowas remained at large. Combined, they mounted about 1,200 warriors.<ref>Utley, Robert M. 1973, ''Frontier Regulars the United States Army and the Indian, 1866-1891'' [https://www.questia.com/library/book/frontier-regulars-the-united-states-army-and-the-indian-1866-1891-by-robert-m-utley.jsp online edition]\n p 211</ref>\n\n===Army response===\n[[File:Texas Panhandle.PNG|thumb|Area comprising locations of the battles in the Texas Panhandle]]\n\nGeneral [[Phillip Sheridan]] ordered five army columns to converge on the general area of the Texas Panhandle and specifically upon the upper tributaries of the [[Red River of the South|Red River]]. The strategy was to deny the Indians any safe haven and attack them unceasingly until they went permanently to the reservations.\n \nThree of the five columns were under the command of Colonel [[Ranald S. Mackenzie]]. The [[10th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|Tenth Cavalry]], under Lieutenant Colonel John W. Davidson, came due west from [[Fort Sill]]. The [[11th Infantry Regiment (United States)|Eleventh Infantry]], under Lieutenant Colonel [[George P. Buell]], moved northwest from [[Fort Griffin]]. Mackenzie himself led the [[4th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|Fourth Cavalry]] north from [[Fort Concho]].\n \nThe fourth column, consisting of the [[6th Cavalry Regiment|Sixth Cavalry]] and [[5th Infantry Regiment (United States)|Fifth Infantry]], was commanded by Colonel [[Nelson A. Miles]] and came south from [[Fort Dodge (US Army Post)|Fort Dodge]]. The fifth column, the [[8th Cavalry Regiment|Eighth Cavalry]] commanded by Major William R. Price, a total of 225 officers and men, plus six Indian scouts and two guides originated from [[Fort Union National Monument|Fort Union]],<ref>Leo E. Oliva: ''Fort Union and the Frontier Army in the Southwest \u2212 A Historic Resource Study''. Division of History \u2212 National Park Service, Santa Fe, New Mexico 1993, [http://www.nps.gov/history/history/online_books/foun/chap7.htm chapter 7]</ref> marched east via [[Fort Bascom]] in New Mexico.<ref>Gwynne, S.C. 2010 ''Empire of the Summer Moon: Quanah Parker and the Rise and Fall of the Comanches, the Most Powerful Indian Tribe in American History'' p. 275-276</ref> The plan called for the converging columns to maintain a continuous offensive until a decisive defeat had been inflicted on the Indians.\n \nAs many as 20 engagements took place across the Texas Panhandle. The Army, consisting entirely of soldiers and scouts, sought to engage the Indians at any opportunity. The Indians, traveling with women, children, and elderly, mostly attempted to avoid them. When the two did encounter one another, the Indians usually tried to escape before the Army could force them to surrender. However, even a successful escape could be disastrously costly if horses, food, and equipment had to be left behind. By contrast, the Army and its Indian scouts had access to essentially limitless supplies and equipment, they frequently burned anything they captured from retreating Indians, and were capable of continuing operations indefinitely. The war continued throughout the fall of 1874, but increasing numbers of Indians were forced to give up and head for Fort Sill to enter the reservation system.\n\n===Battle of Palo Duro Canyon===\n{{Main|Battle of Palo Duro Canyon}}\n[[File:Palo Duro 2002.jpg|thumb|Rugged terrain of the [[Palo Duro Canyon]]]]\nEarly in September, [[Black Seminole Scouts]] in advance of the 4th Cavalry were ambushed by Comanche near the [[Llano Estacado|Staked Plains]] and escaped with their lives. The scouts relayed the Comanche position and put Mackenzie on alert.<ref>{{cite book|last=Schubert|first=Frank N.|title=Black Valor: Buffalo Soldiers and the Medal of Honor, 1870-1898|publisher=Scholarly Resources Inc.|authorlink=Frank N. Schubert|p=[https://archive.org/details/blackvalorbuffal00schu/page/33 33]|date=1997|isbn=9780842025867|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/blackvalorbuffal00schu/page/33}}</ref>\n\nThe largest Army victory came when Mackenzie's scouts found a large village of Comanche, Kiowa, and Cheyenne, including their horses and winter food supply, in upper Palo Duro Canyon. At dawn on September 28, Mackenzie's troops attacked down a steep canyon wall. The Indians were caught by surprise and did not have time to gather their horses or supplies before retreating. Sergeant John Charlton wrote of the battle:\n \n<blockquote>The warriors held their ground for a time, fighting desperately to cover the exit of their squaws and pack animals, but under the persistent fire of the troops, they soon began falling back.<ref>Gwynne, S.C. 2010 ''Empire of the Summer Moon: Quanah Parker and the Rise and Fall of the Comanches, the Most Powerful Indian Tribe in American History'', p. 281</ref></blockquote>\n \nOnly four Indians were killed, but the loss was devastating. Mackenzie's men burned over 450 lodges and destroyed countless pounds of buffalo meat. They also took 1,400 horses, most of which were subsequently shot to prevent the Indians from recapturing them.\n \nExcept for its unusually large size, the Battle of Palo Duro Canyon was typical of the war. Most encounters produced few or no casualties, but the Indians could not afford the constant loss of food and mounts. Even if it escaped immediate danger, an Indian band that found itself on foot and out of food generally had no choice but to give up and head for the reservation.\n\n==Aftermath==\n\nThe Red River War officially ended in June 1875 when Quanah Parker and his band of Quahadi Comanche entered Fort Sill and surrendered; they were the last large roaming band of southwestern Indians. Combined with the extermination of the buffalo, the war left the Texas Panhandle permanently open to settlement by farmers and ranchers.<ref>Utley, Robert M. 1973, Frontier Regulars the United States Army and the Indian, 1866-1891 online edition, p. 211</ref><ref>Haley, James. L. 2009 ''The Red River War'' in ''Handbook of Texas Online'' [http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/qdr02 online]\n</ref> It was the final military defeat of the once powerful Southern Plains tribes and brought an end to the [[Texas\u2013Indian Wars]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Carter, R.G., On the Border with Mackenzie, 1935, Washington D.C.: Enyon Printing Co. {{ISBN|978-0-87611-246-5}}\n* Hutton, Paul. ''Phil Sheridan and His Army'' (1985).\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/lakota_sioux_and_comanche_indians/11627582825/ Map of Red River War 1874-75]\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.texasbeyondhistory.net/redriver/ |title=Red River War |website=Texas Beyond History |publisher=University of Texas at Austin}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.pan-tex.net/usr/p/pampa-hist/red.htm |title=Red River Wars |website=History of Pampa, Gray County, Texas |publisher=Pampa Cyber Net}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.thc.state.tx.us/public/upload/publications/red-river-war.pdf |title=Red River War of 1874-1875 ~ Clash of Cultures in the Texas Panhandle |website=Texas Travel Guide |publisher=Texas Historical Commission}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/qdr02 |title=Red River War |last=Haley |first=James L. |website=TSHA Handbook of Texas Online |publisher=Texas State Historical Association}}\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1874]]\n[[Category:1874 in the United States]]\n[[Category:Comanche tribe]]\n[[Category:Cheyenne tribe]]\n[[Category:Indian wars of the American Old West]]\n[[Category:Comanche Campaign]]\n[[Category:Wars between the United States and Native Americans]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Comanche]]\n[[Category:Presidency of Ulysses S. Grant]]\n[[Category:Red River of the South]]\n", "name_user": "72.203.191.10", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eWar)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_River_War"}
{"title_page": "Ren\u00e9e Gilly", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Ren\u00e9e Gilly\n| image       =\n| image_size  =\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1906|04|29|df=y}}\n| birth_place = Paris, France\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1977|03|31|1906|04|29|df=y}}\n| death_place = Paris, France\n| other_names =\n| education   =\n| occupation  = {{plainlist|\n* Operatic [[mezzo-soprano]]\n* Academic teacher\n}}\n| spouse      = [[Louis Musy]]\n| parents     = [[Dinh Gilly]], [[C\u00e9cile Gilly]]\n| nationality = [[France]]\n}}\n'''Ren\u00e9e Gilly''' (19 April 1906&nbsp;\u2013 31 March 1977) was a French operatic [[mezzo-soprano]]. She was a long-time principal member of the [[Op\u00e9ra-Comique]], where she performed leading roles such as Massenet's [[Werther|Charlotte]], Mascagni's [[Cavalleria Rusticana|Santuzza]], and Bizet's [[Carmen]]. She appeared in world premieres and sang as a guest at major opera houses in Europe.\n\n== Career ==\nGilly was born in Paris, the daughter of [[baritone]] [[Dinh Gilly]] and mezzo-soprano [[C\u00e9cile Gilly]].{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}}  At the age of four she began piano studies with [[Marguerite Long]].{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}} In 1922 at the age of 16 she undertook a series of piano recitals in England. She also served as an accompanist to her father, who participated in a series of conferences concerning singing.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}} At the suggestion of [[Pierre-Barth\u00e9lemy Gheusi]] (later director of the [[Op\u00e9ra-Comique]]) she took up singing, studying with both her father and her mother.{{sfn|Kutsch|Riemens|2012|p=1730}}\n\nShe made her debut at the Op\u00e9ra-Comique in the role of Charlotte in Massenet\u2019s ''[[Werther]]'' on 16 September 1933 and became one of the company's central  performers.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}} Among her roles there were Bizet's [[Carmen]], Santuzza in Mascagni's ''[[Cavalleria Rusticana]]'', Toinette in [[Xavier Leroux]]'s ''Le Chemineau'', Dulcin\u00e9e in Massenet's ''[[Don Quichotte]]'', Jacqueline in Gounod's ''[[Le m\u00e9decin malgr\u00e9 lui]]'', the mother in Charpentier's ''[[Louise (opera)|Louise]]'', the title role in ''[[Mignon]]'' by [[Ambroise Thomas]], Genevi\u00e8ve in Debussy's ''[[Pell\u00e9as et M\u00e9lisande]]'', Panttasil\u00e9e in Xavier Leroux's ''[[La reine Fiammette]]'', Rosette in Massenet's ''[[Manon]]'', Margared in Lalo's ''[[Le roi d\u2019Ys]]'', the title role in Puccini's ''[[Tosca]]'', Salud in de Falla's ''[[La vida breve]]'', and Popp\u00e9e in a French-language version of Monteverdi's ''[[L\u2019incoronazione di Poppea]]''.{{sfn|Kutsch|Riemens|2012|volume=4|p=1730}}\n\nShe participated in six world premieres, among them Magdeleine in [[Antoine Mariotte]]\u2019s ''Gargantua'', Ninon in Hector Fraggi's ''A quoi r\u00eaent les jeunes filles'', and the title role in [[Darius Milhaud]]\u2019s ''Esther de Carpentras''.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}}\n\nShe made her debut with the [[Paris Opera]] at the Palais Garnier on 13 October 1936 in the title role of Massenet's ''[[Herodiade]]''. As part of that company she also sang Ortrud in Wagner's ''[[Lohengrin (opera)|Lohengrin]]'', Br\u00fcnhilde in ''[[Die Walk\u00fcre]]'', Marguerite in ''[[La Damnation de Faust]]'' by Berlioz, Margared in ''Le Roi d\u2019Ys'' and Marina in Mussorgsky's ''[[Boris Godunov (opera)|Boris Godunov]]''.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}} She appeared as a guest in Belgium, at the [[Royal Opera House]] in London, and in the Netherlands, Hungary, Monte Carlo, North Africa, Romania, and Switzerland.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}}{{sfn|Kutsch|Riemens|2012|volume=4|p=1730}}\n\nShe had a powerful voice with exceptional musicality and an excellent technique.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}} Having trained as a pianist, she functioned as an accompanist for her mother's lessons with students. Richard Davis noted that [[Marjorie Lawrence]] was surprised to discover that the person accompanying her during C\u00e9cile Gilly's lessons was her daughter, who then became the teacher responsible for teaching Lawrence actual roles.{{sfn|Davis|2012|p=38}}\n\nOn her retirement from the stage in 1951 she became the chair of the [[Conservatoire de Paris]].  She remained with the Conservatoire until her retirement in 1976.{{sfn|Kutsch|Riemens|2012|volume=4|p=1731}}{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}}\n\nGilly was married to baritone [[Louis Musy]].{{sfn|Kutsch|Riemens|2012|p=1730}} She died on 31 March 1977 in Paris.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Works consulted==\n*{{cite book|last=Davis|first=Richard Michael|title=Wotan's Daughter: The Life of Marjorie Lawrence|location=Kent Town, S. Australia|publisher=Wakefield Press|year=2012|isbn=9781743052105|ref = harv}}\n*{{citation|last=Gourret|first=Jean|title=Dictionnaire des cantatrices de l\u2019op\u00e9ra de Paris|location=Paris|publisher=Editions Albatros|year=1987|oclc= 489575054}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Kutsch\n| first = K. J.\n| authorlink = Karl Josef Kutsch\n| last2 = Riemens\n| first2 = Leo\n| authorlink2 = Leo Riemens\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=dsfq_5dFeL0C&pg=PA1730\n| title = Gilly, Ren\u00e9e\n| work = [[Gro\u00dfes S\u00e4ngerlexikon]]\n| publisher = [[Walter de Gruyter]]\n| edition = 4th\n| language = de\n| year = 2012\n| pages = 1730\u20131731\n| isbn = 978-3-59-844088-5\n| ref = harv\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{DNB portal|135441773}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gilly, Ren\u00e9e}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Paris]]\n[[Category:Opera singers]]\n[[Category:French operatic mezzo-sopranos]]\n[[Category:20th-century French women singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century French opera singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century women opera singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from Paris]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Ren\u00e9e Gilly\n| image       =\n| image_size  =\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1906|04|29|df=y}}\n| birth_place = Paris, France\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1977|03|31|1906|04|29|df=y}}\n| death_place = Paris, France\n| other_names =\n| education   =\n| occupation  = {{plainlist|\n* Operatic [[mezzo-soprano]]\n* Academic teacher\n}}\n| spouse      = [[Louis Musy]]\n| parents     = [[Dinh Gilly]], [[C\u00e9cile Gilly]]\n| nationality = [[France]]\n}}\n'''Ren\u00e9e Gilly''' (19 April 1906&nbsp;\u2013 31 March 1977) was a French operatic [[mezzo-soprano]]. She was a long-time principal member of the [[Op\u00e9ra-Comique]], where she performed leading roles such as Massenet's [[Werther|Charlotte]], Mascagni's [[Cavalleria Rusticana|Santuzza]], and Bizet's [[Carmen]]. She appeared in world premieres and sang as a guest at major opera houses in Europe.\n\n== Career ==\nGilly was born in Paris, the daughter of [[baritone]] [[Dinh Gilly]] and mezzo-soprano [[C\u00e9cile Gilly]].{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}}  At the age of four she began piano studies with [[Marguerite Long]].{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}} In 1922 at the age of 16 she undertook a series of piano recitals in England. She also served as an accompanist to her father, who participated in a series of conferences concerning singing.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}} At the suggestion of [[Pierre-Barth\u00e9lemy Gheusi]] (later director of the [[Op\u00e9ra-Comique]]) she took up singing, studying with both her father and her mother.{{sfn|Kutsch|Riemens|2012|p=1730}}\n\nShe made her debut at the Op\u00e9ra-Comique in the role of Charlotte in Massenet\u2019s ''[[Werther]]'' on 16 September 1933 and became one of the company's central  performers.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}} Among her roles there were Bizet's [[Carmen]], Santuzza in Mascagni's ''[[Cavalleria Rusticana]]'', Toinette in [[Xavier Leroux]]'s ''Le Chemineau'', Dulcin\u00e9e in Massenet's ''[[Don Quichotte]]'', Jacqueline in Gounod's ''[[Le m\u00e9decin malgr\u00e9 lui]]'', the mother in Charpentier's ''[[Louise (opera)|Louise]]'', the title role in ''[[Mignon]]'' by [[Ambroise Thomas]], Genevi\u00e8ve in Debussy's ''[[Pell\u00e9as et M\u00e9lisande]]'', Panttasil\u00e9e in Xavier Leroux's ''[[La reine Fiammette]]'', Rosette in Massenet's ''[[Manon]]'', Margared in Lalo's ''[[Le roi d\u2019Ys]]'', the title role in Puccini's ''[[Tosca]]'', Salud in de Falla's ''[[La vida breve]]'', and Popp\u00e9e in a French-language version of Monteverdi's ''[[L\u2019incoronazione di Poppea]]''.{{sfn|Kutsch|Riemens|2012|volume=4|p=1730}}\n\nShe participated in six world premieres, among them Magdeleine in [[Antoine Mariotte]]\u2019s ''Gargantua'', Ninon in Hector Fraggi's ''A quoi r\u00eaent les jeunes filles'', and the title role in [[Darius Milhaud]]\u2019s ''Esther de Carpentras''.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}}\n\nShe made her debut with the [[Paris Opera]] at the Palais Garnier on 13 October 1936 in the title role of Massenet's ''[[Herodiade]]''. As part of that company she also sang Ortrud in Wagner's ''[[Lohengrin (opera)|Lohengrin]]'', Br\u00fcnhilde in ''[[Die Walk\u00fcre]]'', Marguerite in ''[[La Damnation de Faust]]'' by Berlioz, Margared in ''Le Roi d\u2019Ys'' and Marina in Mussorgsky's ''[[Boris Godunov (opera)|Boris Godunov]]''.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}} She appeared as a guest in Belgium, at the [[Royal Opera House]] in London, and in the Netherlands, Hungary, Monte Carlo, North Africa, Romania, and Switzerland.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}}{{sfn|Kutsch|Riemens|2012|volume=4|p=1730}}\n\nShe had a powerful voice with exceptional musicality and an excellent technique.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}} Having trained as a pianist, she functioned as an accompanist for her mother's lessons with students. Richard Davis noted that [[Marjorie Lawrence]] was surprised to discover that the person accompanying her during C\u00e9cile Gilly's lessons was her daughter, who then became the teacher responsible for teaching Lawrence actual roles.{{sfn|Davis|2012|p=38}}\n\nOn her retirement from the stage in 1951 she became the chair of the [[Conservatoire de Paris]].  She remained with the Conservatoire until her retirement in 1976.{{sfn|Kutsch|Riemens|2012|volume=4|p=1731}}{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}}\n\nGilly was married to baritone [[Louis Musy]].{{sfn|Kutsch|Riemens|2012|p=1730}} She died on 31 March 1977 in Paris.{{sfn|Gourret|1987|p=153}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Works consulted==\n*{{cite book|last=Davis|first=Richard Michael|title=Wotan's Daughter: The Life of Marjorie Lawrence|location=Kent Town, S. Australia|publisher=Wakefield Press|year=2012|isbn=9781743052105|ref = harv}}\n*{{citation|last=Gourret|first=Jean|title=Dictionnaire des cantatrices de l\u2019op\u00e9ra de Paris|location=Paris|publisher=Editions Albatros|year=1987|oclc= 489575054}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Kutsch\n| first = K. J.\n| authorlink = Karl Josef Kutsch\n| last2 = Riemens\n| first2 = Leo\n| authorlink2 = Leo Riemens\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=dsfq_5dFeL0C&pg=PA1730\n| title = Gilly, Ren\u00e9e\n| work = [[Gro\u00dfes S\u00e4ngerlexikon]]\n| publisher = [[Walter de Gruyter]]\n| edition = 4th\n| language = de\n| year = 2012\n| pages = 1730\u20131731\n| isbn = 978-3-59-844088-5\n| ref = harv\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{DNB portal|135441773}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gilly, Ren\u00e9e}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Paris]]\n[[Category:Opera singers]]\n[[Category:French operatic mezzo-sopranos]]\n[[Category:20th-century French women singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century French opera singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century women opera singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from Paris]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ren%C3%A9e_Gilly"}
{"title_page": "HP ProBook", "text_new": "{{short description|Laptop line manufactured by Hewlett-Packard}}\n{{Update|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox computer\n|name               = ProBook series\n|logo               =\n|developer          = [[HP Inc.]]\n|type               = [[Laptop computer|Laptop]]\n|first_release_date = {{Start date|2009|04|28}}\n|photo              =\n|caption            =\n}}\n\nThe '''HP ProBook''' is a brand of business notebooks made by [[Hewlett-Packard]].<ref name=\"ProBook\">{{cite web |first=Ross|last=Miller|title=HP unveils ProBook s-series laptops for the businessperson who needs a bit more power|url=https://www.engadget.com/2009/04/28/hp-unveils-probook-s-series-laptops-for-the-businessperson-who-n/|publisher=Engadget|date=April 2009|accessdate=2 Jun 2011}}</ref> HP marketed the ProBook series to business users; the [[list price]] was lower than that of HP's higher-end [[HP EliteBook|EliteBook]] series.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/02/23/hp-gets-down-to-business-with-redesigned-and-refreshed-elitebook/ |title=HP gets down to business with redesigned and refreshed EliteBook and ProBook laptops (hands-on) |first=Joanna |last=Stern |date=February 2011 |accessdate=4 Jun 2011}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n=== S-Series (discontinued in 2012) ===\nIn April 2009, HP introduced the ProBook s-series (''standard/essential'') notebooks, which consisted of the Intel powered 4410s, 4510s, and 4710s (14\", 15.6\", and 17.3\" screens, respectively) and the [[Advanced Micro Devices|AMD]] powered 4415s and 4515s (14\" and 15.6\" screens, respectively).<ref name=\"ProBook\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hp.com/hpinfo/newsroom/press/2009/090428xa.html |title=Blending Business Chic with Affordability, HP Unveils HP ProBook Notebook PC Line |author=Hewlett-Packard |location=Palo Alto, California |date=April 2008 |accessdate=2 Jun 2011}}</ref> This was followed by the introduction of the 13.3\" ProBook 4310s in June of the same year.<ref name=\"Hewlett-Packard\">{{cite web | url=http://www.hp.com/hpinfo/newsroom/press/2009/090624c.html?jumpid=reg_r1002_usen | title=HP Expands ProBook Family of Notebooks | date=June 24, 2009 | accessdate=November 18, 2011 | author=Hewlett-Packard}}</ref> <br />\nThe s-series was updated in 2010 with Intel Core i3, i5, and i7 processors, a [[Brushed metal|brushed]] aluminum case, [[chiclet keyboard]], and [[multi-touch]] [[touchpad|ClickPad]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2010/03/01/hp-spices-up-probooks-with-core-2010-cpus-clickpads-and-caviar/ |title=HP spices up ProBooks with Core 2010 CPUs, ClickPads and caviar paint |first=Joanna |last=Stern |date=March 2010 |accessdate=2 Jun 2011}}</ref> Updates to the line in 2012 included a new exterior aluminum design.<ref name=\"Wollman, Dana\">{{cite web | url=https://www.engadget.com/2012/05/08/hp-probook-s-series-b-series-refresh/ | title=HP refreshes its ProBook laptops for small businesses | date=May 8, 2012 | accessdate=June 21, 2012 | author=Wollman, Dana}}</ref>\n====4x1xs====\n* ProBook 4310s\n* ProBook 4311s\n* ProBook 4410s\n* ProBook 4411s\n* ProBook 4510s\n* ProBook 4710s\n* ProBook 4415s\n* ProBook 4416s\n* ProBook 4515s\n\n====4x2xs====\n* ProBook 4320s\n* ProBook 4321s\n* ProBook 4420s\n* ProBook 4421s\n* ProBook 4520s\n* ProBook 4720s\n* ProBook 4325s\n* ProBook 4326s\n* ProBook 4425s\n* ProBook 4525s\n\n====4x3xs====\n* ProBook 4230s\n* ProBook 4330s\n* ProBook 4331s\n* ProBook 4430s\n* ProBook 4431s\n* ProBook 4530s\n* ProBook 4730s\n* ProBook 4435s\n* ProBook 4436s\n* ProBook 4535s\n\n====4x4xs====\n* ProBook 4340s\n* ProBook 4341s\n* ProBook 4440s\n* ProBook 4441s\n* ProBook 4540s\n* ProBook 4740s\n* ProBook 4445s\n* ProBook 4446s\n* ProBook 4545s\n\n=== B-Series (discontinued in 2012) ===\nThe ProBook B-series was announced on October 13, 2009, replacing the previous HP Compaq B-series. Two AMD powered models were announced\u2014the 14\" ProBook 6445b and the 15.6\" Probook 6545b.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hp.com/hpinfo/newsroom/press/2009/091013xa.html | title=HP Sets Sights on PC Replacement Cycle | date=October 13, 2009 | accessdate=June 21, 2012 | author=Hewlett-Packard Development Company, L.P.}}</ref> Their Intel powered counterparts were announced three months later as the 14\" ProBook 6440b and the 15.6\" Probook 6540b.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://hpfansite.com/hp-probook/hp-probook-6440b-probook-6540b-official/ | title=HP Probook 6440b and Probook 6540b now official | date=January 6, 2010 | accessdate=June 21, 2012 | author=Soo, Brad}}</ref>  <br />\nThe B-series was updated in 2011 with the Intel-powered 6460b and 6560b, and the AMD-powered 6465b and in 2012 with the Intel-powered 6470b and 6570b, and the AMD-powered 6475b, and the Intel-powered 6555b. <ref name=\"Wollman, Dana\"/>\n\n====6x4xb====\n* ProBook 6440b\n* ProBook 6540b\n* ProBook 6445b\n* ProBook 6545b\n\n====6x5xb====\n* ProBook 6450b\n* ProBook 6550b\n* ProBook 6455b\n* ProBook 6555b\n\n====6x6xb====\n* ProBook 6360b\n* ProBook 6460b\n* ProBook 6560b\n* ProBook 6465b\n* ProBook 6565b\n\n====6x7xb====\n* ProBook 6470b\n* ProBook 6570b\n* ProBook 6475b\n\n===M-Series (discontinued in 2011)===\nHP launched the 5310m in September 2009. The 5310m was enclosed by an aluminum and magnesium case, weighed under four pounds, and was less than an inch thick.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-13924_3-10366950-64.html | title=Windows 7 to usher in crush of cheap laptops | publisher=CNet | date=October 4, 2009 | accessdate=November 18, 2011 | author=Crothers, Brooke}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.engadget.com/2009/09/15/hps-probook-5310m-and-pavilion-dm3-keep-thin-and-light-cheap/ | title=HP's ProBook 5310m and Pavilion dm3 keep \"thin-and-light\" cheap enough for the rest of us | date=September 15, 2009 | accessdate=November 18, 2011 | author=Miller, Paul}}</ref>  <br />\nThe M-series was updated in September 2010 with a 5320m, closely followed with the release of the 5330m in May 2011 which featured a dual-tone aluminum chassis and [[Beats Electronics|Beats]] Audio.<ref name=\"Hewlett-Packard\"/>\n====5x1xm====\n* ProBook 5310m\n\n====5x2xm====\n* ProBook 5220m\n* ProBook 5320m\n\n====5x3xm====\n* ProBook 5330m\n\n===G-Series===\nHP launched the G0 series in 2013. The computers are enclosed in an aluminium and magnesium case. The G1 series succeeded in 2014. \n====G0====\n* ProBook 440 G0\n* ProBook 450 G0\n* ProBook 470 G0\n\n====G1====\nThe G1 series has a 15.6\" non-touchscreen with anti-glare display, a HDD of up to 1-Terabyte storage space, dual memory slots of up to 16GB RAM and a DVD burner. The HDD and RAM can be upgradeable. The G1 series is 0.9\" in thickness and weighs 5.1 pounds. <ref>https://laptoping.com/specs/product/hp-350-g1-laptop/</ref>\n* ProBook x360 11 G1 EE\n* ProBook 430 G1\n* ProBook 440 G1\n* ProBook 450 G1\n* ProBook 470 G1\n* ProBook 445 G1\n* ProBook 455 G1\n* ProBook 640 G1\n* ProBook 650 G1\n* ProBook 645 G1\n* ProBook 645 G1\n* Pro x2 410 G1\n* Pro x2 612 G1\n\n====G2====\nThe G2 series has a 15.6\" anti-glare LED screen, a HDD of up to 1-Terabyte storage space, dual memory slots of up to 16GB RAM which can be upgradeable by the user. The G2 series is 0.13\" and weighs 0.5 pounds.<ref>https://support.hp.com/au-en/document/c04531652#AbT1</ref>\n* ProBook x360 11 G2 EE\n* ProBook 430 G2\n* ProBook 440 G2\n* ProBook 450 G2\n* ProBook 470 G2\n* ProBook 445 G2\n* ProBook 455 G2\n* ProBook 640 G2\n* ProBook 650 G2\n* ProBook 645 G2\n* ProBook 655 G2\n* Pro x2 410 G2\n* Pro x2 612 G2\n\n====G3====\n* ProBook x360 11 G3 EE\n* ProBook 430 G3\n* ProBook 440 G3\n* ProBook 446 G3\n* ProBook 450 G3\n* ProBook 470 G3\n* ProBook 455 G3\n* ProBook 640 G3\n* ProBook 650 G3\n* ProBook 645 G3\n* ProBook 655 G3\n\n====G4====\n* ProBook x360 11 G4 EE\n* ProBook 430 G4\n* ProBook 440 G4\n* ProBook 450 G4\n* ProBook 470 G4\n* ProBook 455 G4\n* ProBook 640 G4\n* ProBook 650 G4\n* ProBook 645 G4\n\n====G5====\n* ProBook x360 11 G5 EE\n* ProBook 430 G5\n* ProBook 440 G5\n* ProBook x360 440 G1\n* ProBook 450 G5\n* ProBook 470 G5\n* ProBook 455 G5\n* ProBook 640 G5\n* ProBook 650 G5\n\n====G6====\n* ProBook x360 11 G6 EE\n* ProBook 430 G6\n* ProBook 440 G6\n* ProBook 450 G6\n* ProBook 445 G6\n* ProBook 445R G6\n* ProBook 455R G6\n\n====G7====\nHP ProBook x360 435 G7 13.3-inch 2-in-1 was announced on January 16, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.notebookcheck.net/HP-ProBook-x360-435-G7-coming-this-Summer-with-AMD-Ryzen-3-4300U-Ryzen-5-4500U-and-Ryzen-7-4700U-options.450366.0.html|title=HP ProBook x360 435 G7 coming this Summer with AMD Ryzen 3 4300U, Ryzen 5 4500U, and Ryzen 7 4700U options|first=Allen|last=Ngo|date=2020-01-16|website=NotebookCheck}}</ref>\n* ProBook 430 G7\n* ProBook 440 G7\n* ProBook 450 G7\n* ProBook 445 G7\n* ProBook 455 G7\n\n==Timeline of releases==\n{| class=\"class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border: 1px solid darkgray;\"\n! colspan=\"100%\" style=\"background: lightyellow\" | Hewlett-Packard ProBook Release Timeline\n|- bgcolor=#AAAAFF\n| '''Screen size'''\n| '''Series'''\n| width=\"100 pt\"| 2009\n| width=\"100 pt\"| 2010\n| width=\"100 pt\"| 2011\n| width=\"100 pt\"| 2012\n| colspan=\"2\" width=\"200 pt\"| 2013\n| width=\"100 pt\"| 2014\n| width=\"100 pt\"| 2015\n| width=\"100 pt\"| 2016\n| width=\"100 pt\"| 2017\n| width=\"100 pt\"| 2018\n| width=\"100 pt\"|2019\n| width=\"100 pt\"|2020\n|- bgcolor=#E0E0E0\n| bgcolor=#F0F0F0| 11.6\"\n| bgcolor=#F0F0F0|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 11 EE G1\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|- bgcolor=#E0E0E0\n| rowspan=\"2\" bgcolor=#F0F0F0 | 12.1\"\n| bgcolor=#F0F0F0| ''s-series''\n|\n|\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 4230s\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|- bgcolor=#E0E0E0\n| bgcolor=#F0F0F0 | ''m-series''\n|\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 5220m\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|- bgcolor=#E0E0E0\n| rowspan=\"3\" bgcolor=#F0F0F0 | 13.3\"\n| bgcolor=#F0F0F0| ''s-series''\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 4310s/4311s\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 4320s/4321s 4325s/