who-n/|publisher=Engadget|date=April 2009|accessdate=2 Jun 2011}}</ref> HP marketed the ProBook series to business users; the [[list price]] was lower than that of HP's higher-end [[HP EliteBook|EliteBook]] series.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/02/23/hp-gets-down-to-business-with-redesigned-and-refreshed-elitebook/ |title=HP gets down to business with redesigned and refreshed EliteBook and ProBook laptops (hands-on) |first=Joanna |last=Stern |date=February 2011 |accessdate=4 Jun 2011}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n=== S-Series (discontinued in 2012) ===\nIn April 2009, HP introduced the ProBook s-series (''standard/essential'') notebooks, which consisted of the Intel powered 4410s, 4510s, and 4710s (14\", 15.6\", and 17.3\" screens, respectively) and the [[Advanced Micro Devices|AMD]] powered 4415s and 4515s (14\" and 15.6\" screens, respectively).<ref name=\"ProBook\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hp.com/hpinfo/newsroom/press/2009/090428xa.html |title=Blending Business Chic with Affordability, HP Unveils HP ProBook Notebook PC Line |author=Hewlett-Packard |location=Palo Alto, California |date=April 2008 |accessdate=2 Jun 2011}}</ref> This was followed by the introduction of the 13.3\" ProBook 4310s in June of the same year.<ref name=\"Hewlett-Packard\">{{cite web | url=http://www.hp.com/hpinfo/newsroom/press/2009/090624c.html?jumpid=reg_r1002_usen | title=HP Expands ProBook Family of Notebooks | date=June 24, 2009 | accessdate=November 18, 2011 | author=Hewlett-Packard}}</ref> <br />\nThe s-series was updated in 2010 with Intel Core i3, i5, and i7 processors, a [[Brushed metal|brushed]] aluminum case, [[chiclet keyboard]], and [[multi-touch]] [[touchpad|ClickPad]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2010/03/01/hp-spices-up-probooks-with-core-2010-cpus-clickpads-and-caviar/ |title=HP spices up ProBooks with Core 2010 CPUs, ClickPads and caviar paint |first=Joanna |last=Stern |date=March 2010 |accessdate=2 Jun 2011}}</ref> Updates to the line in 2012 included a new exterior aluminum design.<ref name=\"Wollman, Dana\">{{cite web | url=https://www.engadget.com/2012/05/08/hp-probook-s-series-b-series-refresh/ | title=HP refreshes its ProBook laptops for small businesses | date=May 8, 2012 | accessdate=June 21, 2012 | author=Wollman, Dana}}</ref>\n====xx1xs====\n* ProBook 4310s\n* ProBook 4311s\n* ProBook 4410s\n* ProBook 4411s\n* ProBook 4510s\n* ProBook 4710s\n* ProBook 4415s\n* ProBook 4416s\n* ProBook 4515s\n\n====xx2xs====\n* ProBook 4320s\n* ProBook 4321s\n* ProBook 4420s\n* ProBook 4421s\n* ProBook 4520s\n* ProBook 4720s\n* ProBook 4325s\n* ProBook 4326s\n* ProBook 4425s\n* ProBook 4525s\n\n====xx3xs====\n* ProBook 4230s\n* ProBook 4330s\n* ProBook 4331s\n* ProBook 4430s\n* ProBook 4431s\n* ProBook 4530s\n* ProBook 4730s\n* ProBook 4435s\n* ProBook 4436s\n* ProBook 4535s\n\n====xx4xs====\n* ProBook 4340s\n* ProBook 4341s\n* ProBook 4440s\n* ProBook 4441s\n* ProBook 4540s\n* ProBook 4740s\n* ProBook 4445s\n* ProBook 4446s\n* ProBook 4545s\n\n=== B-Series (discontinued in 2012) ===\nThe ProBook B-series was announced on October 13, 2009, replacing the previous HP Compaq B-series. Two AMD powered models were announced\u2014the 14\" ProBook 6445b and the 15.6\" Probook 6545b.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hp.com/hpinfo/newsroom/press/2009/091013xa.html | title=HP Sets Sights on PC Replacement Cycle | date=October 13, 2009 | accessdate=June 21, 2012 | author=Hewlett-Packard Development Company, L.P.}}</ref> Their Intel powered counterparts were announced three months later as the 14\" ProBook 6440b and the 15.6\" Probook 6540b.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://hpfansite.com/hp-probook/hp-probook-6440b-probook-6540b-official/ | title=HP Probook 6440b and Probook 6540b now official | date=January 6, 2010 | accessdate=June 21, 2012 | author=Soo, Brad}}</ref>  <br />\nThe B-series was updated in 2011 with the Intel-powered 6460b and 6560b, and the AMD-powered 6465b and in 2012 with the Intel-powered 6470b and 6570b, and the AMD-powered 6475b, and the Intel-powered 6555b. <ref name=\"Wollman, Dana\"/>\n\n====xx4xb====\n* ProBook 6440b\n* ProBook 6540b\n* ProBook 6445b\n* ProBook 6545b\n\n====xx5xb====\n* ProBook 6450b\n* ProBook 6550b\n* ProBook 6455b\n* ProBook 6555b\n\n====xx6xb====\n* ProBook 6360b\n* ProBook 6460b\n* ProBook 6560b\n* ProBook 6465b\n* ProBook 6565b\n\n====xx7xb====\n* ProBook 6470b\n* ProBook 6570b\n* ProBook 6475b\n\n===M-Series (discontinued in 2011)===\nHP launched the 5310m in September 2009. The 5310m was enclosed by an aluminum and magnesium case, weighed under four pounds, and was less than an inch thick.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-13924_3-10366950-64.html | title=Windows 7 to usher in crush of cheap laptops | publisher=CNet | date=October 4, 2009 | accessdate=November 18, 2011 | author=Crothers, Brooke}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.engadget.com/2009/09/15/hps-probook-5310m-and-pavilion-dm3-keep-thin-and-light-cheap/ | title=HP's ProBook 5310m and Pavilion dm3 keep \"thin-and-light\" cheap enough for the rest of us | date=September 15, 2009 | accessdate=November 18, 2011 | author=Miller, Paul}}</ref>  <br />\nThe M-series was updated in September 2010 with a 5320m, closely followed with the release of the 5330m in May 2011 which featured a dual-tone aluminum chassis and [[Beats Electronics|Beats]] Audio.<ref name=\"Hewlett-Packard\"/>\n====xx1xm====\n* ProBook 5310m\n\n====xx2xm====\n* ProBook 5220m\n* ProBook 5320m\n\n====xx3xm====\n* ProBook 5330m\n\n===G-Series===\nHP launched the G0 series in 2013. The computers are enclosed in an aluminium and magnesium case. The G1 series succeeded in 2014. \n====G0====\n* ProBook 440 G0\n* ProBook 450 G0\n* ProBook 470 G0\n\n====G1====\nThe G1 series has a 15.6\" non-touchscreen with anti-glare display, a HDD of up to 1-Terabyte storage space, dual memory slots of up to 16GB RAM and a DVD burner. The HDD and RAM can be upgradeable. The G1 series is 0.9\" in thickness and weighs 5.1 pounds. <ref>https://laptoping.com/specs/product/hp-350-g1-laptop/</ref>\n* ProBook x360 11 G1 EE\n* ProBook 430 G1\n* ProBook 440 G1\n* ProBook 450 G1\n* ProBook 470 G1\n* ProBook 445 G1\n* ProBook 455 G1\n* ProBook 640 G1\n* ProBook 650 G1\n* ProBook 645 G1\n* ProBook 645 G1\n* Pro x2 410 G1\n* Pro x2 612 G1\n\n====G2====\nThe G2 series has a 15.6\" anti-glare LED screen, a HDD of up to 1-Terabyte storage space, dual memory slots of up to 16GB RAM which can be upgradeable by the user. The G2 series is 0.13\" and weighs 0.5 pounds.<ref>https://support.hp.com/au-en/document/c04531652#AbT1</ref>\n* ProBook x360 11 G2 EE\n* ProBook 430 G2\n* ProBook 440 G2\n* ProBook 450 G2\n* ProBook 470 G2\n* ProBook 445 G2\n* ProBook 455 G2\n* ProBook 640 G2\n* ProBook 650 G2\n* ProBook 645 G2\n* ProBook 655 G2\n* Pro x2 410 G2\n* Pro x2 612 G2\n\n====G3====\n* ProBook x360 11 G3 EE\n* ProBook 430 G3\n* ProBook 440 G3\n* ProBook 446 G3\n* ProBook 450 G3\n* ProBook 470 G3\n* ProBook 455 G3\n* ProBook 640 G3\n* ProBook 650 G3\n* ProBook 645 G3\n* ProBook 655 G3\n\n====G4====\n* ProBook x360 11 G4 EE\n* ProBook 430 G4\n* ProBook 440 G4\n* ProBook 450 G4\n* ProBook 470 G4\n* ProBook 455 G4\n* ProBook 640 G4\n* ProBook 650 G4\n* ProBook 645 G4\n\n====G5====\n* ProBook x360 11 G5 EE\n* ProBook 430 G5\n* ProBook 440 G5\n* ProBook x360 440 G1\n* ProBook 450 G5\n* ProBook 470 G5\n* ProBook 455 G5\n* ProBook 640 G5\n* ProBook 650 G5\n\n====G6====\n* ProBook x360 11 G6 EE\n* ProBook 430 G6\n* ProBook 440 G6\n* ProBook 450 G6\n* ProBook 445 G6\n* ProBook 445R G6\n* ProBook 455R G6\n\n====G7====\nHP ProBook x360 435 G7 13.3-inch 2-in-1 was announced on January 16, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.notebookcheck.net/HP-ProBook-x360-435-G7-coming-this-Summer-with-AMD-Ryzen-3-4300U-Ryzen-5-4500U-and-Ryzen-7-4700U-options.450366.0.html|title=HP ProBook x360 435 G7 coming this Summer with AMD Ryzen 3 4300U, Ryzen 5 4500U, and Ryzen 7 4700U options|first=Allen|last=Ngo|date=2020-01-16|website=NotebookCheck}}</ref>\n* ProBook 430 G7\n* ProBook 440 G7\n* ProBook 450 G7\n* ProBook 445 G7\n* ProBook 455 G7\n\n==Timeline of releases==\n{| class=\"class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border: 1px solid darkgray;\"\n! colspan=\"100%\" style=\"background: lightyellow\" | Hewlett-Packard ProBook Release Timeline\n|- bgcolor=#AAAAFF\n| '''Screen size'''\n| '''Series'''\n| width=\"100 pt\"| 2009\n| width=\"100 pt\"| 2010\n| width=\"100 pt\"| 2011\n| width=\"100 pt\"| 2012\n| colspan=\"2\" width=\"200 pt\"| 2013\n| width=\"100 pt\"| 2014\n| width=\"100 pt\"| 2015\n| width=\"100 pt\"| 2016\n| width=\"100 pt\"| 2017\n| width=\"100 pt\"| 2018\n| width=\"100 pt\"|2019\n| width=\"100 pt\"|2020\n|- bgcolor=#E0E0E0\n| bgcolor=#F0F0F0| 11.6\"\n| bgcolor=#F0F0F0|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 11 EE G1\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|- bgcolor=#E0E0E0\n| rowspan=\"2\" bgcolor=#F0F0F0 | 12.1\"\n| bgcolor=#F0F0F0| ''s-series''\n|\n|\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 4230s\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|- bgcolor=#E0E0E0\n| bgcolor=#F0F0F0 | ''m-series''\n|\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 5220m\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|- bgcolor=#E0E0E0\n| rowspan=\"3\" bgcolor=#F0F0F0 | 13.3\"\n| bgcolor=#F0F0F0| ''s-series''\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 4310s/4311s\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 4320s/4321s 4325s/4326s\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 4330s/4331s\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 4340s/4341s\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0 colspan=\"2\"| 430 G1\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 430 G2\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 430 G3\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 430 G4\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 430 G5\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 430 G6\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 430 G7\n|\n|- bgcolor=#E0E0E0\n| bgcolor=#F0F0F0 | ''m-series''\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 5310m\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 5320m\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 5330m\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|- bgcolor=#E0E0E0\n| bgcolor=#F0F0F0 | ''b-series''\n|\n|\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 6360b\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|- bgcolor=#E0E0E0\n| rowspan=\"3\" bgcolor=#F0F0F0 | 14\"\n| bgcolor=#F0F0F0| ''s-series''\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 4410s/4411s 4415s/4416s\n| bgcolor=#C0C0C0| 4420s/4421s 4425s\n| bgcolor